                    <msContents>
                        <summary>Three volumes of woodblock printed sketches of birds, flowers, animals and figures by Kitao Masayoshi(1764-1824); he was also known as Kuwagata Keisai prior to becoming the official painter to the daimyo of Tsuyama in 1797. This work was published in 1801 by Eirakuya Tōshirō of Nagoya. According to Hillier, the artist makes extensive use of the tonal printing effects pioneered by Tachibana Morikuni in his Unpitsu soga 504 (1749), which clearly inspired him. This work is, surprisingly, not listed in Kokusho, Kotenseki or Ehon: all three refer to a work with a similar title, Shinki issō, by the same artist and published with a preface dated 1814, but this must be a different work. Forrer, in his study of the career of Eirakuya Tōshirō, refers to Shinki ipputsu in passing: it is clearly the same work as the present one. Hillier’s index lists Shinki issō but not Shinki ipputsu, although on the pages cited it is Shinki ipputsu that is discussed, not Shinki issō. Brown states that Shinki ipputsu was published in 1800 in one volume and that Shinki issō is a supplementary series to Shinki ipputsu and was published in three volumes in 1804. There is considerable confusion here which cannot be sorted without a close examination of surviving copies of both works. </summary>

